It has SNAT port exhaution problem

NAT: method used by routers and firewalls to remap one IP address space into another by modifying network address information in IP packet headers

Source NAT(SNAT): Changes the source IP address of outgoing packets
Use case:When devices in a private network access the internet, their source IPs (private) are replaced with a public IP.

Destination NAT(DNAT): Changes the destination IP address of incoming packets
Use case: Port forwarding: External users reach a public IP, but the request is forwarded to a specific internal server

How SNAT works in practice
Each unique (source IP, source port, destination IP, destination port, protocol) tuple is a NAT connection.
When many pods/services share the same public IP for outbound connections, each connection must use a different source port.

SNAT Exhaustion Problem:
There are only ~64,000 possible source ports per IP and protocol
In high-scale environments (like AKS clusters with many pods), you can run out of available port numbers for SNAT.
When this happens, new outbound connections cannot be established until old ones close—leading to connectivity issues (timeouts, dropped connections)
How it works in AKS with Load Balancer outbound:
Suppose you have 1 public IP on your Load Balancer.
That IP provides ~64,000 SNAT ports for the whole cluster.
Azure Load Balancer divides these ports among the AKS nodes (VMs). For example, if you have 4 nodes, each node might get ~16,000 SNAT ports
Each node gets a pre-allocated pool of SNAT ports from each public IP
As you increase the number of nodes, each node gets fewer SNAT ports
As you scale up or down the number of nodes in your AKS cluster, Azure dynamically reallocates the available SNAT ports per node
Result:
Outbound connections fail intermittently.
Errors like "connection reset", "cannot assign requested address", etc.
Solution:
1)you can add more public IPs to AKS LB as it supports 64000 ports per IP. increasing IP means increasing ports
2) AKS NAT Gateway mode:
NAT Gateway doesn't pre allocate ports per node. it allocates the port based on demand. one node has more ports that has high outgoing connections
this doesn't solve the problem but reduces it by avoiding pre allocation. we can add more IPs to NAT Gateway also to have more SNAT ports
It acts like LB for outgoing traffic
For traffic from within VNET or peered VNET it doesn't use NAT gateway it uses internal network
