used for stateful application like databases
yaml file same as deployment, under spec it has replicas, selectors and pod template along with service name and volumeclaimtemplates
service name used here is a headless service. it provides stable DNS identities for each pod in statefulset
each pod in sts gets stable DNS name like pod-name-0.servicename.namespace.svc.cluster.local. even if the pod restarts it gets the same pod name and dns name
instead of volumes section and mentioning pvc name inside it in deployment, here in statefulsets its using volumeclaimtemplates directly with specifications of pvc like storageclass, size & accessmode. 

headless service doesn't provide load balancing. it provides direct access to pods by providing dns name.

In deployments all replicas will use the same pvc. In statefulset each replica is attached with separate pvc & pv
The main difference from Deployments is stable identity + automatic PVC creation per pod

when I scale sts replcia from 1 to 3, it will create 2 additional pods, along with 2 other pv and pvc for those pods

persistentVolumeClaimRetentionPolicy:
  whenDeleted: Delete - Policy applied when the StatefulSet itself is deleted to retain/delete the PVC
  whenScaled: Retain - Policy applied when the StatefulSet is scaled down (replicas reduced) to retain/delete the PVC. in retain, if you scale back up, the same PVCs can be reused.
  
Accessmodes in pvc - azure disk only supports readwriteonce mode and its attached to one of the nodes in cluster. where as other storages that supports readwritemany or readonlymany doesn't attached to nodes
for ex. Azure Disk → RWO only, the disk can be mounted as read/write by only one node at a time. multiple pods on the same node can access the same Azure Disk PVC simultaneously
Azure Files / NFS / CephFS → RWX/ROX supported, These are network file systems — they don’t “attach” like a disk; instead, they’re mounted over the network, so multiple nodes can access them at once

Stateful is like running a db vm. image is the vm os. attached pvc is the disk for db data. other deployments or pods can access from the dns name of the replicas. 

if I scaled down my statefulset from 3 to 1 and had retained the pvc. after sometime i scaled up again. in this case each pod will bound to its existing pvc. If the pod is scheduled on a different node, K8s will detach the Azure Disk from the old node and reattach it to the new node. this is true if the azure disk and the new node are in same AZ.
If azure disk is created with LRS (3 replicas in same zone), it couldn't be detached from old node and attached to new node. so the pod will fail to run
If azure disk is created with ZRS (3 replicas across different zones), then only k8s can reattach it to another node where pod runs

Azure Disk with either LRS or ZRS mode could still be mounted with only one node. only one pod can write at a time. RWO. volumemode: filesystem by default
Azure Shared Disk can be attached to multiple nodes, supports RWX. still only one node can write at a time. supports LRS & ZRS. volumemode: Block - specifying this in pvc will create shared disk. 
 
